Install R on your Machine

Below some notes on the installation and setup of R and relevant packages on your own computer:

  • Install Rtools for Windows machines from CRAN (https://cran.r-project.org/bin/windows/Rtools/).
  • If you are using OS X, you will need to to install XCode, available for free from the App Store. This will install a compiler (if you donât have a compiler installed) which will be needed when installing packages from GitHub that require compilation from C++ source code.
  • Install the latest version of R from CRAN (https://cran.r-project.org/).
  • Install the latest version of RStudio (https://www.rstudio.com/products/RStudio/). RStudio is the editor weâll rely on, i.e.Â weâll write code in RStudio which is subsequently sent to and run within R.
  • Install the latest versions of various packages that we need. You can also update your packages by running âupdate.packages(ask = FALSE)â in the R commandline.
# A function to install the required packages
# you don't need to understand what it does
ipak <- function(pkg){
  new.pkg <- pkg[!(pkg %in% installed.packages()[, "Package"])]
  if (length(new.pkg)) 
    install.packages(new.pkg, dependencies = TRUE,repos = c(
  CRAN = 'https://cran.rstudio.com',
  CRANextra = 'https://macos.rbind.io'
)
      )
  sapply(pkg, require, character.only = TRUE)
}

Where to find the materials

Example with the ladone dataset:

Lalonde: Dataset description

  • Analyzed in Lalonde (1986) and Dehejia and Wahba (1999).
  • The âtreatmentâ refers to participation in a employment program (RCT) that took place between 1976 and 1977 to help disadvantage to move into the labour market
  • The âcontrolâ is non-randomized individuals with supposedly same characteristics
  • Employment program (Treatment) -> Earnings
  • DV:
    • re78: real earnings in 1978.
  • Control/Treatment:
    • treat: treatment indicator
  • Background and Pretreatment variables
    • age: age in years.
    • educ: years of schooling.
    • nodegr: indicator variable for high school diploma.
    • black: indicator variable for blacks.
    • hisp: indicator variable for Hispanics.
    • married: indicator variable for martial status.
    • re74: real earnings in 1974.
    • re75: real earnings in 1975.
    • u74: unemployment status 1974.
    • u75: unemployment status 1975.
  • Sample of 614
  • Treatment of 185
  • Control of 429

treatment <- lalonde[lalonde$treat==1,] # subset the treatment observations 
control <- lalonde[lalonde$treat==0,] # subset the control observations 

t.test(treatment$age,control$age) %>% #t test treatment VS control
  report()  -> r_age # generate report

Ladone: Exact Matching

  1. The simplest version of matching is exact.
  2. Match each treated unit to all possible control units with exactly the same values on all the covariates
  3. Creates subclasses such that within each subclass all units (treatment and control) have the same covariate values.
  4. Itâs indicated when your control is bigger than the treatment
  5. Control and treatment groups are quite similar
exact <- matchit(treat ~  age + educ + black + hispan + married + nodegree + re74 + re75, 
  data = lalonde,
  method = "exact")

summary(exact,interactions = TRUE)

Ladone: Nearest Neighbor Matching

  1. Select a number of controls that best matches each individual in the treatment group
  2. It uses a distance measure based on a predicted propensity score (default=logit)

Nearest (and optimal) matching 

nearest <- matchit(treat ~  age + educ + black + hispan + married + nodegree + re74 + re75, 
  data = lalonde, # the data 
  method = "nearest") # the matching method 

reteined_units <- summary(nearest)$nn

kable(reteined_units,digits=2)
Control Treated
All 429 185
Matched 185 185
Unmatched 244 0
Discarded 0 0
  • Many more retained units (185 per each group)
  • Letâs look at the imbalance

Plot the covariate imbalance/balance: Q-Q Plot

  • QQ Plot to empirical quantile-quantile plots.
  • They provide the median, mean, and maximum distance between the empirical quantile functions of the treated and control groups.
  • Values greater than 0 indicate deviations between the groups in some part of the empirical distributions.
  • If the empirical distributions are the same in the treated and control groups, the points in the Q-Q plots would all lie on the 45 degree line
plot(nearest, which.xs = c("age","re74","black"))

plot(nearest,  type = "jitter", 
  interactive = FALSE)

  • It seems that we achieved a decent covariate distribution
  • Q: Is there a variable for which we are not able to do it?

Plot the results of the matching: Jitter plot

  • Overall distribution of propensity scores
  • The size of each point is proportional to the weight given to that unit.
  • It it similar to the previous generated density plot
plot(nearest,  type = "jitter", 
  interactive = FALSE)

Letâs extract the matched data

matched_data <- match.data(nearest)
  • We have only 370 observations left
  • letâs now see how to get the ATT

Estimation of the ATT: Non-Parametric

  • Simple mean difference
  • We donât have a significance level
  • Maybe we should run a paired t.test
  • ORâ¦
mean(matched_data$re78[matched_data$treat == 1]) - mean(matched_data$re78[matched_data$treat == 0])
## [1] 908.2022

Estimation of the ATT: Parametric

  • OLS with dummy indicator
regression_estimate <- lm(re78 ~ treat, data=matched_data)

stargazer(regression_estimate, type="html")

  • DAMN! They are the same.
  • The results are not significant
  • Is it a problem?
  • OLS is like running a paired t-test
  • Easy answer: YES

Estimation of the ATT: Parametric with control

  • OLS with dummy indicator + controls
  • Interpretation is different: The effect of the unemployment programs on real earnings, keeping all the other variables constant
  • Conditional estimates VS Marginal estimates
  • If we subscribe to the experimental logic and the matching is satisfactory
    • We should use marginal estimates
    • We should not condition on other variables
  • However: many researchers use conditional effects in order to guard against variables that we were not able to balance with the matching technique
  • So letâs re-run our estimates with race
regression_estimate_conditional <- lm(re78 ~ treat+black + hispan, data=matched_data)
stargazer(regression_estimate_conditional, type="html")
